{"@context":"http://schema.org/","@type":"Review","itemReviewed":{"@type":"Product","name":"Dyson - V15 Detect Cordless Vacuum - Yellow/Nickel"},"name":"More than just a party trick","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"TaterMcTatums"},"reviewBody":"The main reason I was interested in this is simply because of the Dyson name on it. I am happy to report that it absolutely lives up to its namesake. The Dyson V15 Detect is one of the best vacuums I have ever used, cordless or otherwise. The powerful motor sucks up super fine, silt-like dirt. This is made even better by it being cordless. You can head straight to the mess without having to worry where the nearest outlet is or sacrificing any performance whatsoever. The multiple power modes allow you to select how much cleaning power you need with just a simple button press. I found that Auto mode is great at balancing power consumption with cleaning power and is the mode I almost all the time. The Laser Slim Fluffy cleaner head allows you to see even the smallest specs of dirt so that you never have to worry about missing a spot on your hard floors. I have included a picture of it in action. When you need to clean the carpeted areas of your home, switching heads is literally a snap. The feature I simultaneously love and hate the most is the particle counter on the LCD screen. I love it because it shows you, in real time, how much cleaner your place is becoming. Also, it makes cleaning seem like a game. Watching the numbers and graphs get larger makes you want to keep cleaning, even if for no reason other than seeing how high of a score you can get. I hate it because the high numbers show me how much dirt my other vacuums were leaving behind. During my initial use, I saw particle counts of nearly a billion (see picture). On top of that, I feel like it is shaming me for not cleaning my place as often as I evidently should.

As good as the V15 is, there are some things that I do not like about it. It takes a considerable amount of time to recharge. Going from 30% to a full charge took around 4 hours. Run time on a full charge leaves a bit to be desired as well. If left in Auto mode, you can get around an hour of continuous run time before you need to return it to its dock. If you switch it to boost mode, this time decreases to as little as 20 minutes. To make matters worse, utilizing the laser on the hard floor head shortens usage time even further. During my very unscientific test, vacuuming with the laser on seemed to use around 25% more battery power. With that being said, I believe that one charge will last long enough to clean most houses, provided that you don’t leave it in boost mode. Speaking of which, switching between modes is simple and straightforward but adjusting other settings is a bit more cumbersome. You have to press and hold the button to bring up the menu. Then once you adjust the setting to how you like it, you must press and hold the button for 3 seconds to confirm your choice. This isn’t the most intuitive method, but I suppose that most people will only have to do this once. Another issue is that the collection bin is not very large. I found myself emptying it every 5 minutes or so. Admittedly, this is a hard thing for me to complain about. Having a small collection bin keeps the unit portable and compact. Plus, the only reason it fills up so quickly is because it is doing such a fantastic job at cleaning. Personally, I’d rather empty it constantly than have it leave dirt behind like my other vacuums apparently were. But I did feel like it was worth mentioning.

At the end of the day, it is highly unlikely that you will be disappointed with the Dyson V15 Detect. It will show you dirt and dust you may have missed, clean it up, and tell you how much was there. Just leave it in Auto and let Dyson’s technology do the work for you. Oh, and return it to the dock when you’re finished.","reviewRating":{"@type":"Rating","ratingValue":5,"bestRating":"5"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Best Buy"}}

